olishing. The quiz requires calculating the maximum weekly output for each process to determine the bottleneck. This practical exercise reinforces the concept of bottlenecks and their identification, which is a crucial aspect of the Theory of Constraints [Data: Concepts (1350); Relationships (244)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Optimal suit production strategy for Cut and Stitch (CS) demonstrates TOC application.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The case study of Cut and Stitch (CS) illustrates the application of the Theory of Constraints in determining the optimal production strategy and resource allocation. CS makes two types of suits using skilled tailors and a unique fabric, both of which are in short supply. A linear programming model is used to decide the optimal production mix, with variables for work suits and lounge suits, an objective to maximize contribution, and constraints related to tailors' time, fabric, and production limits. The feasible region and optimal point are identified on a graph, with point B being the optimal point where contribution is maximized. This case study highlights the practical application of TOC in optimizing production processes [Data: Concepts (1679); Relationships (247)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Quizzes reinforce understanding of the Theory of Constraints.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes quizzes designed to test knowledge on the Theory of Constraints. The Theory of Constraints Quiz, for instance, focuses on managing bottlenecks and maximizing throughput contribution. It assesses the learner's ability to identify bottlenecks in production and the appropriate operation of non-bottleneck resources. These quizzes serve as valuable tools for reinforcing the theoretical concepts covered in the chapter and ensuring a comprehensive understanding of TOC [Data: Concepts (1248); Relationships (243)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"TOC's 